	<section class="section section-cream">
		<div class="blog-post reveal">
			<div class="blog-post-meta">
				<p class="meta-info">Published March 28, 2026 · By the Sula Catering Team</p>
			</div>

			<p>Not every Indian dish travels well. Some lose their texture in transit. Some don't hold heat. Some rely on garnishes that wilt the moment they leave the kitchen. After fifteen years of <a href="/corporate">catering Vancouver offices</a>, we've narrowed down the dishes that consistently deliver — the ones that travel beautifully, satisfy mixed dietary needs, and leave a meeting room buzzing.</p>

			<h2>The Vegetarian <em>Crowd-Pleasers</em></h2>

			<h3>Paneer Butter Masala</h3>
			<p>Cubes of fresh paneer in a creamy tomato-cashew sauce with a hint of fenugreek. It travels brilliantly, holds heat, and is universally loved — even by people who claim not to like Indian food.</p>

			<h3>Dal Makhani</h3>
			<p>Black lentils slow-cooked with cream and butter. The flavour deepens as it sits, which makes it the rare dish that actually improves between kitchen and conference room. Pair with rice and naan.</p>

			<h3>Palak Paneer</h3>
			<p>Spinach and paneer in a mildly spiced gravy. Vegetarian, gluten-free, packed with iron — the dish that quietly satisfies the health-conscious without anyone noticing.</p>

			<h3>Chana Masala</h3>
			<p>Chickpeas in a tangy tomato-onion gravy. Fully vegan, naturally gluten-free, high protein. A reliable choice for any office with multiple dietary requirements.</p>

			<h2>The Non-Vegetarian <em>Standards</em></h2>

			<h3>Butter Chicken</h3>
			<p>The undisputed king of Indian corporate catering. Tender <a href="/blog/halal-indian-catering-vancouver">halal chicken</a> in a creamy tomato gravy. If you've never ordered it for a Vancouver office, you're missing the easiest win in the menu.</p>

			<h3>Chicken Tikka Masala</h3>
			<p>Smoky tandoori chicken pieces in a spiced tomato cream sauce. Slightly more robust than butter chicken — better for offices that want a little more heat and depth.</p>

			<h3>Lamb Rogan Josh</h3>
			<p>Slow-cooked lamb in a Kashmiri-style gravy. A premium option for client lunches and high-stakes meetings.</p>

			<h2>The <em>Carbs</em> That Always Work</h2>
			<ul>
				<li>Basmati rice — neutral, fluffy, holds heat</li>
				<li>Vegetable pulao — adds variety, doubles as a vegetarian main</li>
				<li>Naan — soft, foldable, perfect for buffets</li>
				<li>Garlic naan — adds flavour without adding heat</li>
				<li>Roti — for lighter meals or when bread quantity matters</li>
			</ul>

			<h2>The Sides That <em>Pull It Together</em></h2>
			<ul>
				<li>Raita — cooling yogurt with cucumber and mint</li>
				<li>Mango chutney — sweet, tangy, universally loved</li>
				<li>Mixed pickle — adds spice for the brave</li>
				<li>Green salad with lemon dressing — adds freshness</li>
			</ul>

			<h2>The Desserts That <em>Travel</em></h2>
			<p>For office catering, simple desserts beat fancy ones. Gulab jamun, ras malai, and kheer hold up perfectly. Skip dessert that needs to be plated individually — the buffet doesn't have time for it.</p>

			<h2>Putting It Together</h2>
			<p>For an office lunch of 50 people, here's a menu we've delivered hundreds of times:</p>
			<ul>
				<li>Paneer Butter Masala (vegetarian)</li>
				<li>Butter Chicken (halal)</li>
				<li>Dal Makhani (vegetarian, gluten-friendly)</li>
				<li>Basmati Rice</li>
				<li>Garlic Naan</li>
				<li>Mixed Salad with Raita</li>
				<li>Gulab Jamun</li>
			</ul>
			<p>It's a balanced menu with three crowd-pleasers, the right carbs, fresh sides, and a simple dessert. Add a <a href="/cafe-catering">live chai station</a> if your meeting runs into the afternoon.</p>

			<h2>Final Thoughts</h2>
			<p>The best office catering menu isn't the most ambitious — it's the most reliable. Pick dishes that hold heat, work for mixed dietary needs, and don't rely on last-minute plating. <a href="https://sulaindianrestaurant.com/request-a-quote/">Request a quote</a> and we'll build you a menu that always works.</p>

